WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.380 --> 00:00:06.040
Let's take a look at the allocate command.

2
00:00:06.040 --> 00:00:09.980
This is used to dynamically allocate VSAM, non-VSAM,

3
00:00:09.980 --> 00:00:13.920
and hierarchical file system HFS datasets.

4
00:00:13.920 --> 00:00:15.920
So here we have an allocate command

5
00:00:15.920 --> 00:00:19.760
with a whole bunch of operands telling it how to allocate.

6
00:00:19.760 --> 00:00:22.480
And we'll follow that up with the list DS command

7
00:00:22.480 --> 00:00:24.960
for the dataset that we just created.

8
00:00:24.960 --> 00:00:26.920
And we can see that the record format

9
00:00:26.920 --> 00:00:28.800
and the logical record length match

10
00:00:28.800 --> 00:00:30.760
along with some other information.

11
00:00:30.760 --> 00:00:33.000
It's important to note that the list DS command

12
00:00:33.020 --> 00:00:34.620
will return different information

13
00:00:34.620 --> 00:00:38.180
for VSAM and non-VSAM datasets.

14
00:00:38.180 --> 00:00:40.020
You can also use the delete command

15
00:00:40.020 --> 00:00:42.100
to delete that dataset, like this.

16
00:00:43.020 --> 00:00:46.380
And then if you enter the dslist test.data,

17
00:00:46.380 --> 00:00:49.420
it will come back and say it's not in catalog.

18
00:00:49.420 --> 00:00:50.780
That's a nice way of saying,

19
00:00:50.780 --> 00:00:53.400
I have no knowledge of that particular dataset,

20
00:00:53.400 --> 00:00:55.700
so I can't give you any information about it.

21
00:00:55.700 --> 00:00:59.020
Because the catalog is, it's just like a catalog.

22
00:00:59.020 --> 00:01:02.180
It makes a list of frequently accessed datasets,

23
00:01:02.180 --> 00:01:04.120
so if it's not in the catalog,

24
00:01:04.120 --> 00:01:07.000
we can't find it by name alone.

25
00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:09.480
And if you're curious about the catalog,

26
00:01:09.480 --> 00:01:11.760
you can use the list cat command

27
00:01:11.760 --> 00:01:14.600
to list all the entries in the catalog.

28
00:01:14.600 --> 00:01:17.200
When you type list cat with no operands,

29
00:01:17.200 --> 00:01:19.680
you get a listing of all the catalog entries

30
00:01:19.680 --> 00:01:23.320
associated with your specific user ID.

31
00:01:23.320 --> 00:01:25.880
As you can imagine, there are many other operands

32
00:01:25.880 --> 00:01:27.680
you can use with the list cat.

33
00:01:27.680 --> 00:01:30.600
And you can find them either by using the help commands

34
00:01:30.600 --> 00:01:32.580
or by looking them up in the manual.

35
00:01:33.460 --> 00:01:35.700
Then there's list alc.

36
00:01:35.700 --> 00:01:38.740
This shows you the currently allocated datasets.

37
00:01:38.740 --> 00:01:40.380
When you run it with no operands,

38
00:01:40.380 --> 00:01:44.280
it shows you all the currently allocated dataset names.

39
00:01:44.280 --> 00:01:47.280
If you throw in status after list alc,

40
00:01:47.280 --> 00:01:49.740
it'll show you the status of each dataset,

41
00:01:49.740 --> 00:01:54.100
which includes the termination disposition of the datasets.

42
00:01:54.100 --> 00:01:56.740
It looks like we're trying to keep a lot of them here.

43
00:01:56.740 --> 00:01:59.340
And if you type list alc history,

44
00:01:59.340 --> 00:02:02.120
you get the creation date, expiration date,

45
00:02:02.120 --> 00:02:05.440
and the dataset protection for all those datasets.

46
00:02:05.440 --> 00:02:06.900
That's a handy one.

47
00:02:06.900 --> 00:02:08.520
It's important to realize the difference

48
00:02:08.520 --> 00:02:10.640
between free and delete.

49
00:02:10.640 --> 00:02:13.720
And you'll see how that works here along with catalog.

50
00:02:13.720 --> 00:02:16.740
So we'll start out with another allocate command,

51
00:02:16.740 --> 00:02:19.220
which we've shortened to aloc here.

52
00:02:19.220 --> 00:02:23.100
Then we list ds the dataset to see its information.

53
00:02:23.100 --> 00:02:26.080
Next, we follow that with a free command.

54
00:02:26.080 --> 00:02:29.680
And what this does is it deallocates the datasets

55
00:02:29.680 --> 00:02:32.180
or HFSs that are no longer needed.

56
00:02:32.180 --> 00:02:34.580
It basically says, I don't need this anymore.

57
00:02:34.580 --> 00:02:36.160
It can be freed.

58
00:02:36.160 --> 00:02:39.100
It also means that it can be used for output processing

59
00:02:39.100 --> 00:02:40.800
or routed to another user.

60
00:02:41.880 --> 00:02:45.100
We can then go and delete it with the delete command.

61
00:02:45.100 --> 00:02:49.620
And again, the list ds shows that it's not in the catalog.

62
00:02:49.620 --> 00:02:51.780
There are some restrictions and suggestions

63
00:02:51.780 --> 00:02:55.260
about what types of datasets can, can't, should,

64
00:02:55.260 --> 00:02:58.360
and shouldn't be deleted or freed.

65
00:02:58.360 --> 00:03:00.920
And I bet you know where to find that information.

66
00:03:04.330 --> 00:03:07.690
Okay, let's talk about the profile command.

67
00:03:07.690 --> 00:03:09.690
This command establishes, changes,

68
00:03:09.690 --> 00:03:12.010
or lists your user profile,

69
00:03:12.010 --> 00:03:14.810
basically how you want to use your terminal.

70
00:03:14.810 --> 00:03:18.210
In this example, the message ID is on.

71
00:03:18.210 --> 00:03:19.890
There's some other information in there

72
00:03:19.890 --> 00:03:22.170
like the prefixing, prompting,

73
00:03:22.170 --> 00:03:24.730
and primary and secondary languages.

74
00:03:24.730 --> 00:03:26.370
You can use the profile command

75
00:03:26.470 --> 00:03:28.710
to not only display your profile settings,

76
00:03:28.710 --> 00:03:30.390
but also to change them.

77
00:03:30.390 --> 00:03:31.950
These changes will remain valid

78
00:03:31.950 --> 00:03:34.150
for the duration of your session.

79
00:03:34.150 --> 00:03:36.470
Lastly, the submit command.

80
00:03:36.470 --> 00:03:38.750
This is how we send one or more jobs

81
00:03:38.750 --> 00:03:40.830
to the system for processing.

82
00:03:40.830 --> 00:03:44.750
Each job submitted must reside either in a sequential dataset,

83
00:03:44.750 --> 00:03:46.790
a direct access dataset,

84
00:03:46.790 --> 00:03:49.250
or in a member of a partition dataset,

85
00:03:49.250 --> 00:03:53.090
unless you use the asterisk function of a submit command.

86
00:03:53.090 --> 00:03:55.590
That asterisk function tells the command

87
00:03:55.650 --> 00:03:58.610
that you will enter the data in some other way.

88
00:03:58.610 --> 00:04:00.130
In the lab that follows this,

89
00:04:00.130 --> 00:04:03.450
we'll get to issue some TSO commands on a live system,

90
00:04:03.450 --> 00:04:05.690
which is almost certainly going to be more exciting

91
00:04:05.690 --> 00:04:07.490
than watching me talk about them.
